That with respect to Report C2025-0901, the following amendment be adopted: ;
That a new sub-bullet be inserted under Recommendation 1, as follows: ;
Allocating ;$9.0 ;million in one-time operating funding to Community Services in 2026, to be funded from Fiscal Stability Reserve for the purpose of improving transit safety, and direct Administration to: ;
i. Focus security enhancements on C-Train stations during afternoon rush hour (4 PM  8 PM), based on incident data;
ii. Implement Tiered Security Model as outlined in the Public Transit Safety Strategy:





Transit Peace Officers (TPOs): Mobile patrols, enforcement, complex calls; provide rapid response and support to static guards;
Corporate Security: Fixed posts at priority stations for observation, reporting, and customer assistance;
Contracted security guards: Scalable resource for ;additional ;fixed posts during expansion ;phase; ;





iii. Use phased approach to deploy security staff until additional peace officers are hired (aligned with growth strategy from 2024);
iv. Increase community outreach activities by adding six officers to the Community Outreach Team; and
v. Report back to Council Q3 2026 with results to determine if public perceived C-train was safer as a result

That with respect to Report C2025-0901, the following Motion Arising be adopted: ;
That Council:

Agree in principle that the municipal share of provincial traffic fine revenue should be fully restored, and the reduction of photo radar services be reviewed against outcomes;
Express Councils intention that any restored revenue be earmarked for traffic-safety improvements, including but not limited to safer intersections, crosswalk upgrades, school-zone protections, and traffic-calming measures;
Request the Mayor to communicate Councils position to the Government of Alberta and to work collaboratively with the Minister of Justice, Minister of Municipal Affairs, and Minister of Transportation and Economic Corridors on an updated traffic fine revenue framework and photo radar service framework that restores municipal funding and supports community safety; and
Direct Administration to report back through Infrastructure and Planning Committee with options for allocating any restored revenues toward priority capital safety projects once provincial decisions are known.

